One of Rummer's homes in Beaverton is for sale at $569,900.

They ask only that you love them. And they love you back.

Via Working Mother Magazine: "The benefit would allow couples who make $500,000 or less and single parents earning $250,000 or less to fully deduct the cost of childcare from their taxes. Lower-income families who don't have a tax liability would be eligible for up to $1,200 in Earned Income Tax Credit spending rebates.

The measures are aimed at helping families cope with today's exorbitant childcare costs. At an average of $9,589 per year, infant care now carries a higher price tag than college in 33 states.

However, critics note that the plan stands to benefit middle-income families more than low-income ones."

status_message:
Orange & Dark Chocolate Pound Cake: YUM! http://trib.al/1CkPfok

For the cake:
1 cup butter, softened, plus more for greasing the pan
2 cups sugar
2 oranges, zested
4 eggs
1 cup buttermilk* 
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
3 cups flour
1 teaspoon baking powder
1 teaspoon salt
1/2 teaspoon baking soda
1 1/2 cups dark chocolate chips
* If you don't have buttermilk, combine 1 cup regular milk with 1 tablespoon white vinegar or lemon juice. Let thicken for five minutes.

For the sauce:
1 cup confectioners sugar 
2 oranges, juiced
1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
1/2 cup butter

Preheat your oven to 325 degrees. Grease a nine-inch square pan well with butter or nonstick baking spray.

First the cake. Place the butter, sugar, and orange zest in a large mixing bowl. Use an electric hand mixer to combine the ingredients until light and fluffy. Then, add the eggs one at a time, scraping down the sides of the bowl after each addition. Add the vanilla extract, followed by the buttermilk.

In a separate bowl, combine the flour, baking powder, baking soda and salt. Whisk well to evenly distribute the ingredients.

Slowly add the flour mixture to the wet ingredients. Mix until just combined, and then stir in the chocolate chips. Pour the batter into the greased pan. Smooth the top with a spatula.

Place the pan in the oven and bake for 55-65 minutes, or until a skewer inserted into the cake comes out clean.

Meanwhile, make the butter sauce. Combine the confectioners sugar, orange juice, and remaining butter with a whisk in a small sauce pan. Heat over a medium flame until melted and thick; do not boil.

Use a long skewer to poke many holes in the cake. Slowly spoon the butter sauce over the cake, pausing to let the sauce absorb into the cake.

Let the cake cool completely. Slice and serve.

This recipe will yield one cake with about twelve slices.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
On Dec. 7, 1941, Japan bombed Pearl Harbor. 

The West Coast, where 90 percent of Japanese residents lived at the time, braced for an attack on the mainland. Oregon's governor commanded all people of Japanese descent to remain in their homes. Portlanders prepared for war. Japanese men who showed up for work the next day were told they no longer had jobs. City workers canceled the licenses of many Japanese-owned businesses.

FBI agents patrolled homes and arrested people who had anything Japanese. They confiscated Sakamoto's Brownie camera, leaving him unable to document the years to come.

"That was a hysterical period," Henry "Shig" Sakamoto said. "All the Japanese families just started throwing away anything Japanese."
link_name: He was born in Portland. An executive order sent him to a Japanese internment camp.

"His early memories were formed behind barbed wire fences.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
He remembers the soldiers with their rifles. The tower guards with their searchlights. The tarpaper barrack he lived in with his uncles, mother and siblings. The rough, unfinished wood floors.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
He pictures childhood friends and games played in the dust. Empty thread spools fashioned into makeshift toy cars, and tiddlywinks made from milk cartons. And the camp rule he learned quickly and early on: Never venture beyond the barbed wire.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
He is my grandfather. Sam Matsumoto spent four years in a remote desert internment camp on the Oregon-California border during World War II, part of a West Coast roundup that sent more than 100,000 people - two-thirds of them American citizens - to confinement because of their Japanese heritage.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
His family - and the family of his future wife, my grandmother Harriet Matsumoto - were forced from their Sacramento-area homes to the Tule Lake camp, which at its peak held more than 18,000 people. With wartime fear racing through the nation, the Japanese were told they were enemies of the country. They were charged with no crime and given no due process.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
President Franklin D. Roosevelt's executive order 9066 on Feb. 19, 1942, set the roundups into motion. It authorized regional Army commanders to remove anyone from "military areas" - ultimately the entire West Coast -- as they saw fit. Within six months of the executive order, all people of Japanese ancestry were evacuated from their homes and taken to one of 10 remote camps."‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Read the full story: ow.ly/gNB03099kus

Story by Samantha Keiko Matsumoto

status_message:
Mania Asadizadeh will see her sister again.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
The Portland State University graduate student moved to the United States from Iran a decade ago. She has been trying ever since to bring her sister, Mona Asadizadeh, to live with her.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Mona traveled to Turkey and back for interviews with embassy officials. She filled out reams of paperwork. A few months ago, her visa application was approved.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
When she tried to board a plane last week, a guard stopped her. President Donald Trump temporarily banned visitors from Iran and six other Muslim majority countries.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Mona's visa required her to make it to the United States by April 11 -- before the travel ban expired. Mania believed she might never see her sister again.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Their fates began to change last week when Washington's attorney general filed a lawsuit against Trump, calling the travel ban illegal and unconstitutional. U.S. District Judge James Robart, a George W. Bush appointee in Seattle, issued a temporary order Friday banning enforcement nationwide of the travel ban.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Full story: ow.ly/hUuY308Mvpi
‚†Ä
Story by Casey Parks

Pay no attention to that tubby, elitist, East Coast rodent who, earlier today, said we were in for six more weeks of winter.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
#punxsutawneyphil, the Pennsylvania groundhog who garners the spotlight every #GroundhogDay, was flat wrong, local sources said.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
A hog of the hedge variety, the @oregonzoo's own winter-predicting rodent FuFu, failed to see her shadow Thursday morning, meaning here in the Pacific Northwest, we are in for an early #spring.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Animal curator Tanya Paul, who oversaw Thursday's prediction, said groundhogs aren't even the original animals used to predict the onset of spring, so anything Phil says should be taken with a grain of salt, assuming they aren't using all of it on their icy highways.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
"Groundhogs like Punxsutawney Phil are relative newcomers to the game," Paul said. "According to folklore, the Europeans who originated the tradition originally used #hedgehogs. When they immigrated to the United States, they realized their new home didn't have hedgehogs, so they turned to the groundhog out of necessity. But FuFu is bringing the holiday back to its origins."‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Not only are hedgehogs the original weather predictors, they're also better at it, Paul said. Phil's predictions have been accurate about 39 percent of the time, the zoo said, while our own rodents are closer to 50 percent.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
"The zoo's hedgehogs have fared slightly better than Punxsutawney Phil -- which admittedly is not that great," Paul said in a statement. "Last year though, our hedgehog Velda did predict an early spring, which was pretty accurate for this region. We had the warmest February and April on record."

status_message:
Ursula K Leguin: "A recent letter in The Oregonian compares a politician's claim to tell 'alternative facts' to the inventions of science fiction. The comparison won't work. We fiction writers make up stuff. Some of it clearly impossible, some of it realistic, but none of it real - all invented, imagined --  and we call it fiction because it isn't fact. We may call some of it 'alternative history' or 'an alternate universe,' but make absolutely no pretense that our fictions are 'alternative facts.'

Facts aren't all that easy to come by. Honest scientists and journalists, among others, spend a lot of time trying to make sure of them.  The test of a fact is that it simply is so - it has no 'alternative.'  The sun rises in the east.  To pretend the sun can rise in the west is a fiction, to claim that it does so as fact (or 'alternative fact') is a lie.

A lie is a non-fact deliberately told as fact.  Lies are told in order to reassure oneself, or to fool, or scare, or manipulate others. Santa Claus is a fiction.  He's harmless. Lies are seldom completely harmless, and often very dangerous.  In most times, most places, by most people, liars are considered contemptible."
link_name: Ursula Le Guin on fiction vs. 'alternative facts': Letter to the editor

Mountains mean a lot to us in the #PacificNorthwest. They represent a great power, a certain #sacred presence that lords high above our cities and towns. We make trips to their highest slopes. We drink water from their glacial melt. We can see their silhouettes when we close our eyes. Here's to the many #mountains of #Oregon, a part of our souls from near or from far.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Here's how Oregon's mountains got their names: #ThreeSisters‚†Ä
‚†Ä
There's no official record of who named the beautiful Cascade peaks, but a popular story is that they were called Mount Faith, Mount Hope and Mount Charity (north to south) ‚Äì and collectively called Three Sisters by members of a Methodist mission in Salem in the 1840s.  ‚†Ä

status_message:
Season of Sharing 2016: Oregon Food Bank's school pantries help feed minds and bodies

In Oregon, almost a third of schoolchildren regularly face hunger. The Oregon Food Bank operates 28 school pantry programs, which gives low-income families access to produce and food staples they might not be able to afford.

The pantries are run by volunteers, and the food is almost all donated from grocery stores and food manufacturers, so costs are mostly limited to food transportation.

Read more and donate here: http://s.oregonlive.com/eDu87nW
link_name: Season of Sharing -- Food Bank

This image in our archives has the caption "Survivors of Dec. 7 1941, Japanese attack of Pearl Harbor, which set off World War II, met Saturday morning in Colonial House of Pancakes for informal breakfast honoring dead of event. Session opened with minute of silence and prayer. About 40 of the 100 survivors in the Portland area and their wives attended."

It was taken by staff photographer Frank Sterrett in 1963 -- but the individuals in the photo aren't identified. Do you remember any of the Pearl Harbor attack survivors? If you know them, please include names, hometowns and their position in the photo ("third from left, back row") in the comments or a private message.

status_message:
"It was silently making people sick. It is negligence. We're paying dearly for it."

Every time a soldier pulled the trigger inside a National Guard gun range, a bullet cast off bits of lead. An 18-month investigation by The Oregonian/OregonLive has found that the Guard's neglect allowed toxic dust to spread, endangering soldiers and visitors to America's armories.

Read the full story: ow.ly/J4IU306KoY6

status_message:
The Defense Department and state National Guard officials knew about these toxic armories for nearly two decades but moved slowly to address the problem, leaving soldiers, civilian employees and children exposed, records and interviews show.

Inspectors have found lead dust at alarming levels in armory gyms, drill halls, conference rooms, hallways, stairwells, kitchens, pantries, offices, bathrooms and a day care center.

Read our full #ToxicArmories Watchdog report: http://trib.al/CpmhgG8

Armories in big cities and small towns have housed tearful deployments, joyful reunions and thousands of community events. They're civic landmarks, where part-time soldiers drilled one weekend a month and fired weapons at indoor shooting ranges.

But the firearms emitted an insidious form of lead every time a bullet left the chamber. The National Guard's neglect allowed the dust to spread beyond the ranges, into common areas used by the public, including small children most at risk.

Read more about #ToxicArmories: http://trib.al/CpmhgG8
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:

It's #OregoniansGive day! Donate to the Oregon Food Bank's school pantries here: http://s.oregonlive.com/eDu87nW

The school pantries help feed minds and bodies, and the effort is part of our annual Season of Sharing holiday fundraising campaign.

In Oregon, almost a third of schoolchildren regularly face hunger. The Oregon Food Bank operates 28 school pantry programs, which gives low-income families access to produce and food staples they might not be able to afford.

The pantries are run by volunteers, and the food is almost all donated from grocery stores and food manufacturers, so costs are mostly limited to food transportation.
link_name: Season of Sharing -- Food Bank

status_message:
The Charles Nelson House, Wasco County, Oregon.  The fresh wheat has been harvested and the house remains empty, as it has since 1949. In 1926 Charles E. Nelson acquired the house, which was built in the early 1900s. Ownership passed to Charles' daughter, who sold the property in 2004. The property was leased by a local farmer who planted wheat this year, as others have done over the past century. The rolling hills and proximity to the road make it favorite subject for photographers.

#historic #oldhouse #wascocounty #thedalles #dufur #vintage #pnw #notiphone #charlesnelsonhouse #wasco #oregon

status_message:
All (Portland Police Bureau Gang Enforcement officer) Jason Hubert wanted to do was talk about failure.

"Let's start with no one in a gang gets a pass," he said. "They make the choice. But why do they make that choice? 

When a kid makes a wrong turn and ends up in a gang, that child was let down by people and institutions." He rattles off the culprits: broken families, people in the city who don't give a damn because gangs happen in a neighborhood far from their own, schools that don't serve their students, and even the police.

The police?

Yes," Hubert said. "But we're working to change that."

Go inside Portland's gang world with Tom Hallman Jr.: ow.ly/KfIm303b15h

status_message:
With the holidays nearly over and 2015 receding in the rearview mirror, it's time to look ahead to the new year and, inevitably, the resolutions that go along with it. What's your goal for 2016: Drink less? Lose weight? Not make resolutions?

Whatever the Achilles heel of choice, a solution generally requires a little ‚Ä¶ help. That's where you come in! Below we've listed 10 of the most common New Year's resolutions. Chances are, some of you have had success with some of them. We want to hear how you did it and what advice you can pass on to the newly resolved in their quest for improvement. Add your tips in the comments below, and we'll gather them all up into one informative, helpful story. Crowdsourcing at its best!

‚óè Exercise/eat healthier/lose weight
‚óè Spend less, save more
‚óè Spend more time with family & friends
‚óè Learn something, get a new hobby
‚óè Read more
‚óè Get organized/simplify
‚óè Quit drinking
‚óè Spend less time on electronics 
‚óè Manage stress better
‚óè Volunteer more

While you're formulating your wisdom, check out this post from last year of 17 New Year's resolutions for a real Portlander: http://bit.ly/1NMcP7i

status_message:
What to do with all those leftover Easter eggs? Get into the Holy spirit with these Divine Deviled Eggs (recipe below). Or if you're feeling a little more wicked, try Deviled Eggs From Hell, made with fiery chipotle chiles: http://ORne.ws/1Pa8gal

Divine Deviled Eggs With Fresh Rosemary
Makes 24 servings

Ingredients
12 medium eggs, hard-cooked and peeled
6 tablespoons light mayonnaise
2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
2 teaspoons apple cider vinegar
2 teaspoons finely chopped fresh rosemary leaves
1/8 teaspoon ground black pepper
1/8 teaspoon salt, or more to taste
Instructions
Slice each egg in half lengthwise and scoop out the yolks into a medium bowl. Place the whites on a plate or tray and set aside.

Mix the remaining ingredients into the yolks with a fork, mashing the yolks until it forms a somewhat smooth paste.

Using a pastry bag and decorative tip or a zipper-top bag with one end snipped, swirl the yolk filling back into the egg white halves. Serve at once, or cover and refrigerate for up to 12 hours.

‚Äî Alicia Ross, Kitchen Scoop

"While I am standing there, watching the ocean and noticing the changes that had been made, it dawned on me the water at my feet was being pulled out rapidly. I looked up and realized the water was coming back in ‚Ä¶ I started running up toward my car. Half way, I turned to look just as the waves struck the bridge and threw stumps and logs over it."

Thursday marks 50 years since a magnitude-9.2 earthquake devastated Alaska. Four hours later on the Oregon Coast at about 11:35 p.m.  The sky was clear, the moon full, and the tide nearly high. Then, the ocean pulled back far into itself, and gathering force, roared forth, thundering on to shore.

Story, photo gallery: http://ORne.ws/1hUGQmb

Bad news: The photo below identified by one of our Facebook friends as her grandmother is not actually her grandmother. 

Our researcher, Lynne Palombo, tracked down a copy of the story as it ran in the newspaper -- with the correct name.  

When we contacted the woman who had claimed it was her Nanny, Lois Colwell, she said, "OOPS, so sorry, we have a copy of the photo and we were told many years ago that that was our beloved grandmother.  Very embarrassing!  Again, sorry for the mistake.  I think I'll leave the photo in my scrap book though! :)"

This post has been edited to avoid misinformation.  Please see the new story in the comments below.

status_message:
"Two weeks ago, I toured the 9/11 Tribute Center and listened as a tour guide, a man who worked at the twin towers and managed to escape that morning, walked us through the grounds. Here's what he had to say at the close of the tour:
"The symbolic color of the Tribute Center is blue because of the sky on 9/11 and, for me, it carries the additional meaning of the good blue skies that are in my future. I am nearly 67 years old and older than most anyone here. If I believe I have many good blue skies left, imagine how many you have left."
Today in Portland the sky is as bright and blue as it was that unforgettable morning in New York. Here's to good blue skies, and to the memory of all who lost their lives that day. #Sept11 #remembrance" 
 
-- From our photographer, Beth B. Nakamura

Are mosquitoes just the price you pay for wetland restorations?

Bandon is experiencing a plague of mosquitoes. A dog returned home to its owner covered with a black coat of insects. A boy was bitten so badly he developed welts. A woman's hands had swollen so much her wedding ring was cut off. And a house painter uses a beekeeper's suit to work outside.

The problem has been traced to a $10 million marsh restoration at the Bandon Marsh National Wildlife Refuge. Salmon and shorebirds have returned, but so have the bugs.

status_message:
Cherrie Letter would call the funeral home to ask about the murdered prostitute. For 26 years the answer remained the same. The young woman's family never claimed her ashes. 

A Friday in August 1987, screams brought Letter running out the door of a restaurant where she was talking with a friend. Letter saw 25-year-old Jennifer Lisa Smith lying naked in the parking lot -- the final victim of Oregon's most prolific serial killer, Dayton Leroy Rogers. 

Last week, Letter, struggling with cancerous tumors throughout her body, was finally able to lay Smith's ashes to rest with the smallest service in the funeral home's history.

"I felt such profound sadness," Letter said. "No one cared."

But she did. 

http://ORne.ws/165wJnT

Hussein Omari has endured more struggles than many people twice his age. He was 11 when his father was shot to death in their home in Congo. At 15, he arrived in Portland as a refugee, along with his mother and siblings. He came not able to read or write English and with an infected broken leg.

Two weeks ago, with his siblings at school, he was home alone with his mother, Aisha Mwinja, as she lost her battle to cancer. He had no money to call an ambulance and feared generating a bill his family couldn't pay. So he called the Africa House. Since then the refugee community has joined others in an unprecedented effort to help the six orphaned children who have suffered so much already.

status_message:
The Sellwood Bridge is about to move, shifting into its place as a detour while a new bridge is built. On Jan. 19, a team of engineers, supervisors and skilled workers will activate 10 hydraulic jacks that will lift the 3,400-ton bridge two inches off its concrete piers. In the 12 hours after, they plan to seamlessly pull off one of the longest bridge moves ever attempted. 

"If you love bridges, this is what it's all about," said Jason Kunkle, a foreman with Stayton-based Slayden Construction. "It's a once-in-a-lifetime project." 

Story by Dana Tims and photos by Randy L. Rasmussen: http://orne.ws/sellwood-bridge-prep

Around 1890, loggers chopped down a redwood near Eureka, California, creating one of the world's largest stumps: 32.5 feet wide at chest height, probably 2,000 years old, a base for a tree that may have topped 400 feet. 

Next Tuesday, clones grown from that stump -- will be planted on the Oregon Coast. With hopes to battle climate change by tapping the huge trees' unmatched ability to store carbon. The idea hinges on the as-yet scientifically unproven theory that the ancient redwoods and giant sequoias will prove genetically superior to younger, smaller cousins.

status_message:
Even in the face of adversity, many Oregonians are finding things to be thankful for. This Thanksgiving week, we present a daily portrait of a person sharing what he or she is thankful for. 

Meet Keenan Browne, 27, who was born with tunnel vision and is legally blind. He says it's worsened over the years. He can see only a very small area in the center of his line of sight. At night he can't see anything. Browne is thankful for having his own place to live - a room in the downtown Portland's Stewart Hotel. Browne, who was homeless for five years, said his situation was especially miserable during the cold and rainy seasons. When he would find a warm place to stay, someone would always tell him to go away. He bruised his shins from running into things. He said it was both humbling and embarrassing. Still, Browne knew many people had it worse than he did. Browne is especially thankful for his good friend from Kentucky who supported him while he was getting his Social Security back on track so he could afford rent. "It's really beautiful to have your own keys," Browne says.

See the series: http://ORne.ws/thankful-2012

World War II veteran Wally Tharp made a request that seemed incredibly simple: Move an American flag from the left pole to the right pole in front of the war memorial at the Vancouver Barracks. "I know a lot of people would say the hell with it," said Tharp, now 92. "But for the past 14 years, this has been my life." 

Wednesday morning, Tharp raised the flag and watched it fly in its rightful place.

status_message: Welcome to The Oregonian's Facebook page.

Brian McMillan of Bend climbs the route known as Magic Light at Smith Rock State Park in Terrebonne, Oregon. 

There are more than 1400 climbing routes in and around the park ranging from some of the best sport climbs in the world so don't try this at home. The rocks are a magnificent sight to see, even if you don't plan on climbing. Jagged peaks, the highest some 550 feet, loom over a deep canyon and the Crooked River.
